Solution If we make the substitution $x \to \frac{1}{x}$ then we get $f\left(\frac{1}{x}\right) + \frac{1}{x}f(x) = \frac{1}{x}$ 

 So then we have the system 
 \begin{align*}
f(x)+xf\left(\frac{1}{x}\right)&=x\\
 \frac{1}{x}f(x) + f\left(\frac{1}{x}\right) &=\frac{1}{x}
\end{align*} 


 Multiplying the second relation by $x$ yields $f(x) + xf\left(\frac{1}{x}\right) = 1$ But from the first relation we know that this is $x$ so we must have that $\boxed{x=1}$ 

 Remark While that was probably the intended method in my opinion the question is horribly flawed I'm not quite sure if it is fixable

Solution Drawing XY we see that $\angle AXY+\angle BXY=60+30=90$ thus circles A and B are orthogonal Let $x$ be the area of the section that we are trying to find Then the area of sector $XY$ of circle A plus the area of sector $XY$ of circle B minus $x$ is the area of quadrilateral $AXBY$ (because A and B are orthogonal) We also have the radius of circle B to be $\frac{2\sqrt3}{3}$ because $\angle XBY=120^\circ$ and drawing the height from B of triangle XYB we get two 30 60 90 triangles $[AXBY]=[AXY]+[XYB]=\sqrt{3}+\frac{\sqrt{3}}{3}=\frac{4\sqrt3}{3}$ Thus we have 
 \begin{align*}\frac{4\pi}{6}+\frac{\frac{4\pi}{3}}{3} x&=\frac{4\sqrt3}3 \\
x&=\boxed{\frac{10\pi 12\sqrt3}{9} }
\end{align*}

Solution Outline Use sum of cubes factorization on the first two terms factor out the $a c$ and then use Simon's Favorite Factoring Trick \begin{align*}
 (a b)^{3}+(b c)^{3}+(c a)^{3}&=(a c)(a^2+b^2 2ab+b^2+c^2 2bc ab+ac+b^2 bc)+(c a)^3 \\
&=(a c)(a^2+3b^2+c^2 3ab 3bc+ac) (a c)^3 \\
&=(a c)(a^2+3b^2+c^2 3ab 3bc+ac a^2 c^2+2ac) \\
&=(a c)(3b^2 3ab 3bc+3ac)\\
&=3(a c)(b a)(b c) \\
&=\boxed{3(a b)(b c)(c a)}
\end{align*}

