Removing from my feed if you need me to edit something please PM me To justify the existence of this post here's the solution to 7 the most immature problem I've seen in a while * an SMT organizer who said "oops we're short on problems" and decided to wrap $\zeta(2)=\tfrac{\pi^2}{6}$ into a convoluted intimidating problem—equivalently an elementary schooler who just learned about the aforementioned equation and overexcitedly turned it into an "original" "thought provoking" problem 
 \begin{align*}
\sqrt{6\sum_{t=1}^\infty\left(1+\sum_{k=1}^\infty\left(\sum_{j=1}^\infty(1+k)^{ j}\right)^2\right)^{ t}}&=\sqrt{6\sum_{t=1}^\infty\left(1+\sum_{k=1}^\infty\frac{1}{k^2}\right)^{ t}}\\
&=\sqrt{6\sum_{t=1}^\infty\left(1+\frac{\pi^2}{6}\right)^{ t}}\\
&=\sqrt{6\cdot\frac{1}{\frac{\pi^2}{6}}}=\sqrt{\frac{36}{\pi^2}}=\boxed{\frac{6}{\pi}} \end{align*}

