To maximize laziness the trick for these kinds of problems is to check the extremes as in a symmetric inequality Here those extremes are adding all the rows first (cp $x=k$ $y=z=\dots=0$ ) and adding the rows and columns in alternating fashion (cp $x=y=\dots$ ) The former costs $19\cdot1^2+19\cdot20^2=7619$ the latter costs 
 \begin{align*}
1^2+2^2+2^2+3^2+\dots+19^2+20^2&=2(1^2+\dots+20^2) (1^2+20^2)\\
&=\tfrac{20\cdot21\cdot41}{3} (1+400)\\
&=5740 401=\boxed{5339} \end{align*}

The condition implies $\angle CAB = \angle ABE$ However notice that $\angle EBA = \angle ABD$ due the definition of reflections Therefore $\angle BAC = \angle ABC$ so $\triangle ABC$ is isosceles with $BC = 6$ Let $T = \angle BAC$ then $2T = \angle EBC$ By Law of Cosines we have that 
 \begin{align*}
6^2 = 3^2 + 6^2 2 \cdot 3 \cdot 6 \cdot \cos \left(T\right) \quad \longrightarrow \quad \cos \left(T\right) = \tfrac{1}{4} \end{align*} By Angle Bisector Theorem \begin{align*}
\dfrac{AB}{BD} = \dfrac{AC}{CD} \quad \longrightarrow \quad \dfrac{3}{BD} = \dfrac{6}{CD} \quad \longrightarrow \quad \dfrac{3}{BD} = \dfrac{6}{6 BD} \quad \longrightarrow \quad BD = 2 \text{ }CD = 4 \end{align*} Thus $BE = BD = 2$ Notice $\sin\left(T\right) = \tfrac{\sqrt{15}}{4}$ so $\cos\left(2T\right) = \cos^2\left(T\right) \sin^2\left(T\right) = \tfrac{7}{8}$ By Law of Cosines we have \begin{align*}
CE = \sqrt{BC^2 + BE^2 2 \cdot BC \cdot BE \cdot \cos \left(2T\right)} = \sqrt{6^2 + 2^2 2 \cdot 6 \cdot 2 \cdot \tfrac{7}{8}} = \boxed{\sqrt{61}} \end{align*}
